attributes.title: Submission for Retouching Exercise
attributes.body: The adjective I choose was sinister. First, I adjusted the brightest whites in the picture down to a subtle grey using the levels tool. Next, I removed the antenna from the top of the house using clone stamp. Using the distort twirl filter, I slightly twisted all the trees in the photo. The red wood looked entirely to wholesome, so I adjusted the hue and saturation way down for just the red color on the house and fence. I also dulled the green grass color down to a kind of brownish, without heavily effecting the green of the trees. I also tried to darken the door and windows but did not have much success using the burn tool. Finally, I added some noise for effect and cropped the picture.

attributes.subject: Feedback from sza5730
attributes.body: Very unique. I loved how you brought in some techniques we learned in the beginning of the course; I had actually forgot about them myself. It's very abstract, but I love how the colors of the historical photo matches that of the original.

attributes.subject: Feedback from jrl5491
attributes.body: Hey Brian- Love the abstract nature of this and the blue color scheme.  The piece has a bit of a historical feel that reminds me of some of the photo manipulations we read about in lesson 1 and our historical mashing project.  I'd love to see how you could incorporate the postage markings into the next iteration and play into the theme of tech, communication, distance, etc.  One thing I think would be interesting is to incorporate images other than the building and foreground imagery into the overall collage.  Maybe an overlay of a different historical item, or even a modern photo to juxtapose with the background.  Just a thought!

attributes.subject: Feedback from sjm5892
attributes.body: I am absolutely enveloped by this vintage theme you have here. I honestly can't tell where the original image starts and ends, or where the editing and additions were made. Whatever adjustments you made, I could have not done it better myself. The only thing that stands out a bit too much for me is the orange bit of the image, although it is a good complimentary color for blue, I feel like it may be a bit too over saturated. But I also thinks it adds to the abstract charm of this piece as well, so it's hard to tell. Otherwise, wonderful and very creative thinking. Great job!!!

attributes.subject: Feedback from jcc6017
attributes.body: Very interesting work, Brian!  I love the layering of the top image over the one below.  This approach could work great for images with hidden meanings or messages attached to them.  Nice work!

attributes.subject: Feedback from efl5204
attributes.body: Brian, I really like how this assignment turned out!  You went in a direction I would've never thought of. Your technique of layering circular cutouts on top of another image reminds me of Connect 4! I also like the different hues of color you used throughout your work. Great job!

attributes.subject: Feedback from kzf5346
attributes.body: Brian, I really enjoy how you chose to combine your images. The saturated hues had a psychedelic feel to them and the slow transition between the road and the motorcade were smooth with that neat glitch feel. Considering the history of this particular  Kennedy photo, I was left with eerie vibes and reminded of the Saltz article about selfies in "forbidden" scenarios. You tied in this week's lesson very well. Great work!

attributes.subject: Feedback from glk5123
attributes.body: Whoa! This is very in depth and well executed! I feel like you put your own thoughts and opinions into this by just watching the gif animate. I Like the reference of the saturation in the first part to the historical reference of Kennedy. Great work!
